Tutorial: Factors

P4 REEU // Natalie Nelson, PhD

1. Overview and learning objectives

This tutorial reviews factors, a data type in R, and functions in the forcats package. The forcats package is in the tidyverse family of packages and includes functions specifically for working with factors. This tutorial is closely derived from Chapter 15 Factors in R for Data Science by Garrett Grolemund and Hadley Wickham.

After completing this module, you will be able to:

  • Define: factors, levels

  • Apply the following functions: factor(), levels(), fct_recode(), fct_relevel(), fct_reorder()

Lets get started! 

library(tidyverse)


2. What are factors?


Factors are a data type or class in R, just like character, double, integer, and logical. The factor data type is used when working with categorical data. Categorical data consist of groups/categories. For example, the Palmer Penguins dataset includes several factor columns, shown as <fctr> when the first few rows are previewed:

# Load the palmerpenguins package, which includes the penguins dataset
library(palmerpenguins)
# Look at the head of penguins
head(penguins)
## # A tibble: 6 x 8
##   species island bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_ body_mass_g sex  
##   <fct>   <fct>           <dbl>         <dbl>            <int>       <int> <fct>
## 1 Adelie  Torge           39.1          18.7              181        3750 male 
## 2 Adelie  Torge           39.5          17.4              186        3800 fema
## 3 Adelie  Torge           40.3          18                195        3250 fema
## 4 Adelie  Torge           NA            NA                 NA          NA <NA> 
## 5 Adelie  Torge           36.7          19.3              193        3450 fema
## 6 Adelie  Torge           39.3          20.6              190        3650 male 
## #  with 1 more variable: year <int>

species, island, and sex are factor vectors, meaning these columns consist of categorical data. If we run unique(penguins$species), we can see that categories in species include: Adelie, Gentoo, and Chinstrap. Each unique species represented in the dataset is one category. You will also see something new in the output: Levels: Adelie Chinstrap Gentoo. Well review this in a moment.

Similarly, the island column includes each unique location as a category: Torgersen, Biscoe, Dream. sex includes two categories, male and female, or three if you count NA as a unique category.

Factors are usually composed of character (<chr>) data, but differ from character data in that there are defined levels that correspond to the unique categories in the data. Numeric (<dbl>, <int>) data can also be treated as factors with unique levels, but R cannot perform mathematical operations on factors. As a result, if a numeric vector is converted to a factor, R will treat the vector as character data.

The key advantage to working with factors is the ability to manipulate levels, or categories, represented in the data. The rest of this tutorial will focus on creating factors, defining levels, and reordering levels.


3. Converting a column to a factor: factor()

Imagine you have a character vector composed of a few months:

x <- c("Dec", "Apr", "Jan", "Mar")

This vector is included in a dataframe with values corresponding to a set of measurements:

d <- data.frame(months = x,
                measurements = c(4, 2, 7, 1))
d
##   months measurements
## 1    Dec            4
## 2    Apr            2
## 3    Jan            7
## 4    Mar            1

If we made a barplot to visualize the data (months mapped to the x-axis, measurements mapped to the y-axis), the months would sort in alphabetical order by default:

ggplot(data = d) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = months, y = measurements),
           stat = "identity")

To change the order of the months, we have to specify an order to the categories or levels in the months column. We can fix this issue by converting the months column to a factor using the factor() function. factor() includes many arguments that can be specified, but at a minimum only requires the column to be converted.

# Apply the factor function to a vector object
x_fct <- factor(x)
x_fct
## [1] Dec Apr Jan Mar
## Levels: Apr Dec Jan Mar

factor() can also be used with dataframes:

# Apply the factor function to a dataframe column
factor(d$months)
# Here we are just looking at the output, we would
# have to redefine d$months for the column to be 
# converted to a factor

# Create a new column with month as a factor
d %>%
  mutate(months_factor = factor(months))
# Again, we are just looking at the output, we
# have not redefined d to include this column yet

If you look at the contents of x_fct in the console, you will see that, in addition to the contents of the vector, the levels are also shown as Levels: Apr Dec Jan Mar. Here, the unique levels included in the data are shown and listed in the order that R has sorted them by default (which is alphabetical). The order of the levels also reflects the order in which the months were plotted in the barplot above.

Rather than have the factor() function default to ordering the levels alphabetically, we can specify what the levels are using the levels = argument. The levels = argument requires a vector of the level names included in quotation marks. R will preserve the order in which the levels are specified.

x_fct2 <- factor(x,
                levels = c("Jan", "Mar", "Apr", "Dec"))
x_fct2
## [1] Dec Apr Jan Mar
## Levels: Jan Mar Apr Dec

The order of the levels will transfer to the plot:

d %>%
  mutate(months_factor = factor(months,
                                levels = c("Jan", "Mar", "Apr", "Dec"))) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = months_factor, y = measurements),
           stat = "identity")


3.1. Working with numeric factor data

In section 2, I said you could convert numeric data to factors, but that R would treat the factor data as characters. Which is to say, mathematical operations could not be applied to the numeric factors. As a result, converting a numeric vector to a factor fundamentally changes how the vector can be handled; the values in the vector are essentially treated as category labels instead of numbers. This contrasts with character vectors: when a character vector is converted to a factor, the way R treats the data is essentially unchanged, except R will recognize that there are specific levels in the vector.

Below, an example is shown in which R throws an error message after trying to apply a mathematical operation to a vector of integers.

# Create an integer vector
numbers <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
# Convert to a factor
numbers_fct <- factor(numbers)
# Inspect the data type and class:
# Note that R recognizes the data 
# are integers, but also factors
str(numbers_fct)
##  Factor w/ 5 levels "1","2","3","4",..: 1 2 3 4 5
typeof(numbers_fct)
## [1] "integer"
class(numbers_fct)
## [1] "factor"
# Can't apply mathematical functions
# to the factor
sum(numbers)
sum(numbers_fct)
numbers^2
numbers_fct^2


4. Specifying extra levels

Another special feature of factors is that factor levels can include categories that are not represented in the data. For example, instead of defining the levels for x_fct as the months represented in the data (only Apr, Dec, Jan, and Mar), we could have instead defined the levels to include all conceivable categories:

x_fct3 <- factor(x,
                levels = c(
                  "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", 
                  "Apr", "May", "Jun", 
                  "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", 
                  "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"
                ))
x_fct3
## [1] Dec Apr Jan Mar
## Levels: Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec

Why would you specify all conceivable levels? There are two main reasons I am aware of:

  • Quality control: When you specify factor levels, you are also specifying which values can be included in the vector. If R encounters a value in the vector that is not included in the defined levels, it will replace the value with NA. As a result, we can use levels to flag problematic or inconsistent entries (e.g.typos):
x_typo <- c("Dec", "Apr", "Jam", "Mar", "October")

factor(x_typo,
       levels = c(
         "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", 
         "Apr", "May", "Jun", 
         "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", 
         "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"
       ))
## [1] Dec  Apr  <NA> Mar  <NA>
## Levels: Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec
  • Save time for future-you: Defining factors is often done as part of the data cleaning process when youre first reading your data into R. Two key advantages to running data analyses with scripts as opposed to point-and-click software programs is that you can quickly re-run analyses as new data are generated, and apply your scripts to other datasets. To avoid having to edit your code each time new data are created or each time you want to apply your script to a new dataset, you can define the levels to include all expected values. Your future self will thank you.


5. Inspect levels: levels()

To inspect a factor vectors levels and level order, you can use the levels() function. The levels() function only requires one argument: the name of the factor vector you wish to inspect. levels() differs from unique() in that it shows all defined levels in the order they were specified (or, if the levels were not specified, they will be shown in alphabetical order). The output to unique() shows unique values included in the vector, and the values are printed in the order in which they occur in the vector.

q <- c("Apr", "May", "Jan", 
       "Jan", "Nov", "Jul")
q_fct <- factor(q,
                levels = c(
                  "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", 
                  "Apr", "May", "Jun", 
                  "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", 
                  "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"
                ))
levels(q_fct)
##  [1] "Jan" "Feb" "Mar" "Apr" "May" "Jun" "Jul" "Aug" "Sep" "Oct" "Nov" "Dec"
unique(q_fct)
## [1] Apr May Jan Nov Jul
## Levels: Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec


6. Recoding factor values: fct_recode()

If you want to change factor level names, which will also change the names in your dataframe object, you can use the fct_recode() function. You unfortunately cannot pipe directly into this function unless you specifically pipe a single column (see example below). Instead, you have to use it with mutate(). Note that, with the mutate() function, if you define a column name that already exists in the dataframe, the column will just be overwritten; mutate will not add a new column unless the column has a distinct name. This can be seen in the example below.

The arguments to fct_recode() are structured as follows:

fct_recode(
  dataframe$column_name,
  "New name for level 1" = "Current name of level 1",
  "New name for level 2" = "Current name of level 2"
)

As an example, we can recode the factor levels in the island column of the penguins dataframe. Here, we will add Island to the name of each island, e.g."Biscoe" will become "Biscoe Island".

penguins %>%
  mutate(island = fct_recode(island,
                             "Biscoe Island" = "Biscoe",
                             "Dream Island" = "Dream",
                             "Torgersen Island" = "Torgersen")) -> penguins_fct
penguins_fct
## # A tibble: 344 x 8
##    species island      bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_ body_mass_g
##    <fct>   <fct>                <dbl>         <dbl>            <int>       <int>
##  1 Adelie  Torgersen            39.1          18.7              181        3750
##  2 Adelie  Torgersen            39.5          17.4              186        3800
##  3 Adelie  Torgersen            40.3          18                195        3250
##  4 Adelie  Torgersen            NA            NA                 NA          NA
##  5 Adelie  Torgersen            36.7          19.3              193        3450
##  6 Adelie  Torgersen            39.3          20.6              190        3650
##  7 Adelie  Torgersen            38.9          17.8              181        3625
##  8 Adelie  Torgersen            39.2          19.6              195        4675
##  9 Adelie  Torgersen            34.1          18.1              193        3475
## 10 Adelie  Torgersen            42            20.2              190        4250
## #  with 334 more rows, and 2 more variables: sex <fct>, year <int>
levels(penguins_fct$island)
## [1] "Biscoe Island"    "Dream Island"     "Torgersen Island"

Alternatively, instead of using a pipeline as shown above, you can also redefine the column in the dataframe:

penguins$island <- fct_recode(penguins$island,
                              "Biscoe Island" = "Biscoe",
                              "Dream Island" = "Dream",
                              "Torgersen Island" = "Torgersen")

Or pipe the column vector into fct_recode():

penguins$island %>% 
  fct_recode("Biscoe Island" = "Biscoe",
             "Dream Island" = "Dream",
             "Torgersen Island" = "Torgersen")


7. Reordering factor levels: fct_reorder(), fct_relevel()

As you work on an analysis, you may discover that you would like to reorder factor levels. This typically occurs in the process of creating a data visualization. Before diving into reordering levels, lets start with an example. A Bob Ross example. For those of you who arent familiar with Bob Ross, he was a painter who hosted a TV show called The Joy of Painting. He has been described as the ultimate calming presence.


In 2014, Walt Hickey published A Statistical Analysis of the Work of Bob Ross on FiveThirtyEight, a data journalism organization. Walts study sought to answer the question: which features showed up most frequently in the 403 episodes of The Joy of Painting? Happy little trees? Fluffy clouds? The dataset he created to perform this analysis is included in the fivethirtyeight package as a dataframe object, bob_ross. Load fivethirtyeight and bob_ross to your workspace, and use the code below to summarize and plot the data. The dataset is organized such that there is one row per episode, and one column for each keyword characterizing the episode. The keywords describe painted elements (e.g., aurora_borealis, beach), stylistic choices in framing the paintings, and guest artists. In the keyword columns, there is either a 1 or 0 to indicate whether the keyword did or did not apply to the episode, respectively.

With the code below, you will collapse the keyword columns into two: keyword and count. The count column will include the total number of times the keywords described the 403 episodes. The long-format data will be saved to a new object named bob_ross_features. The keyword column is then converted to a factor and the levels are not specified, meaning they will be ordered alphabetically by default. These data are then plotted.

library(fivethirtyeight)
# Summarize
bob_ross %>%
  pivot_longer(apple_frame:wood_framed,
               names_to = "keyword",
               values_to = "count") %>%
  group_by(keyword) %>%
  summarize(count = sum(count)) %>%
  ungroup() -> bob_ross_features
# Convert the keyword column to a factor
bob_ross_features$keyword <- factor(bob_ross_features$keyword)
levels(bob_ross_features$keyword)
##  [1] "apple_frame"        "aurora_borealis"    "barn"              
##  [4] "beach"              "boat"               "bridge"            
##  [7] "building"           "bushes"             "cabin"             
## [10] "cactus"             "circle_frame"       "cirrus"            
## [13] "cliff"              "clouds"             "conifer"           
## [16] "cumulus"            "deciduous"          "diane_andre"       
## [19] "dock"               "double_oval_frame"  "farm"              
## [22] "fence"              "fire"               "florida_frame"     
## [25] "flowers"            "fog"                "framed"            
## [28] "grass"              "guest"              "half_circle_frame" 
## [31] "half_oval_frame"    "hills"              "lake"              
## [34] "lakes"              "lighthouse"         "mill"              
## [37] "moon"               "mountain"           "mountains"         
## [40] "night"              "ocean"              "oval_frame"        
## [43] "palm_trees"         "path"               "person"            
## [46] "portrait"           "rectangle_3d_frame" "rectangular_frame" 
## [49] "river"              "rocks"              "seashell_frame"    
## [52] "snow"               "snowy_mountain"     "split_frame"

# Visualize
ggplot(data = bob_ross_features) +

From the plot, we can see that there are a few keywords that more commonly describe The Joy of Painting episodes. It takes some effort to read the plot and determine which keywords show up most frequently. To make the plot easier to read, we can reorder the keyword factor levels so that the levels are sorted based on values in the count column.

To reorder the keyword levels based on values in the count column, we can use fct_reorder(). The arguments to fct_reorder() include the factor vector you want to modify, and a numeric vector you want to use to reorder the levels. In this case, the factor vector we want to reorder is bob_ross_features$keyword, and the numeric vector we want to use to reorder the factor levels is bob_ross_features$count.

# Levels before reordering:
levels(bob_ross_features$keyword)

##  [4] "beach"              "boat"               "bridge"

## [10] "cactus"             "circle_frame"       "cirrus"

## [25] "flowers"            "fog"                "framed"            
## [28] "grass"              "guest"              "half_circle_frame" 
## [31] "half_oval_frame"    "hills"              "lake"              
## [34] "lakes"              "lighthouse"         "mill"              
## [37] "moon"               "mountain"           "mountains"         
## [40] "night"              "ocean"              "oval_frame"

Note that, when reordering factor levels, the order of values in the dataframe remains unchanged. All we are changing is the way in which R sorts the level names.

Now that the data are reordered, lets plot the data once again:

ggplot(data = bob_ross_features) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = count, y = keyword))

This reordered plot makes it easier to see that the keywords most commonly describing episodes were (happy little) trees by far, followed by clouds, mountains, and lakes.

Another handy function for reordering factor levels is fct_relevel(). fct_relevel() is a bit more versatile than fct_reorder() in that it can reorder levels in a few ways.

The most simple use of fct_relevel() is to specify a new position(s) for a level(s). The help documentation for fct_relevel() uses the following example:

f <- factor(c("a", "b", "c", "d"), levels = c("b", "c", "d", "a"))
fct_relevel(f, "a")
## [1] a b c d
## Levels: a b c d
fct_relevel(f, "b", "a")
## [1] a b c d
## Levels: b a c d

In this example, fct_relevel(f, "a") is used to bring a to the first level position. fct_relevel(f, "b", "a") is used to bring b to the first level position, and a to the second level position. When fct_relevel() is used in this way, without specifying additional arguments, the function assumes you want to bring the specified levels to the first level positions.

Alternatively, you can specify the precise location of the level using an argument after =. With this argument, you indicate which level position comes before the position you want to move the level to. For example, if we wrote fct_relevel(f, "a", after = 2), this code would be interpreted as: move level a after the second level position. Said another way, move level a to the third position. If you want to move the level to the last level position, set after = to Inf (which stands for infinity).

# Move to the second position
fct_relevel(f, "a", after = 1)
## [1] a b c d
## Levels: b a c d
# Relevel to the end
fct_relevel(f, "c", after = Inf)
## [1] a b c d
## Levels: b d a c

Lastly, fct_relevel() can be used with a function like sort() or rev(). sort() will arrange values in descending order, whereas rev() will reverse the order of the values such that the last element becomes the first, second to last becomes the second, etc. The name of the function is included as an argument, and the function name is listed without parentheses. See below for examples.

k <- factor(c("bravo", "delta", "foxtrot",
              "echo", "alfa", "charlie"),
            levels = c("bravo", "delta", "foxtrot",
              "echo", "alfa", "charlie"))
levels(k)
## [1] "bravo"   "delta"   "foxtrot" "echo"    "alfa"    "charlie"
# Sort levels in ascending order (i.e. alphabetical)
fct_relevel(k, sort)
## [1] bravo   delta   foxtrot echo    alfa    charlie
## Levels: alfa bravo charlie delta echo foxtrot
# Sort levels in reverse order
fct_relevel(k, rev)
## [1] bravo   delta   foxtrot echo    alfa    charlie
## Levels: charlie alfa echo foxtrot delta bravo

  • Adelie: Pygoscelis adeliae

  • Gentoo: Pygoscelis papua

  • Chinstrap: Pygoscelis antarctica

levels(penguins$species)
## [1] "Pygoscelis adeliae"    "Pygoscelis antarctica" "Pygoscelis papua"
